WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
We are watching enterprise AI evolve in real time.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:13.000
The chatbots that used to just answer our questions are being replaced by agents designed to execute autonomous actions.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.000
We are talking about software that can independently book international flights,

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
execute high-frequency financial trades, or permanently alter a customer database.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
When an AI strictly gives advice, the stakes are relatively manageable.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
If a chatbot suggests a bad trade and strategy, the human user who chooses to execute that trade still holds the ultimate responsibility.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
But when an AI bypasses the human and executes an action directly on behalf of a business,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
the liability transfers entirely to the enterprise.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
If that automated action causes a financial loss or triggers a liability dispute,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
the enterprise has a very narrow window to prove exactly what happened.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
A claims reviewer is going to ask two immediate questions.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
What did the customer originally ask the AI to do?

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And what exact action did the AI propose in response?

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Because these systems process thousands of autonomous decisions per minute,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
human oversight for every single transaction is physically impossible.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Risk teams and insurers are left staring at a massive blind spot.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Without a way to mathematically prove the specific sequence of an AI's decision,

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:27.000
agentic commerce remains an uninsurable risk.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
On the left is standard deterministic software logic.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
On the right is the non-deterministic logic of an AI model.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Traditional logs track that deterministic side perfectly, recording what a server executed.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
But they completely fail to capture the human intent driving the AI.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
These standard logs generate simple, easily modified text files.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:54.000
They record the output, but they discard the context necessary to defend why a specific commercial decision was made.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
In a liability dispute, bringing a mutable text file to a claims review

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
is like bringing a word document to a contract negotiation.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
It quickly devolves into a he-said-she-said argument that courts simply will not accept.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Adding basic guardrails to try and stop bad behaviour does not fix the underlying problem.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
If you do not capture immutable proof of the interaction itself, the enterprise remains legally exposed when a failure slips through.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:26.000
You cannot successfully underwrite or legally defend a non-deterministic system with opaque, easily altered activity logs.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:32.000
The absence of verifiable context renders post-incident investigations entirely useless.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Fixing this liability gap requires a completely new type of infrastructure.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.000
It requires an immutable evidence layer built specifically for the nuances of AI workflows.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
This is the Obrioxia architecture.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
The foundation, evidence capture, takes raw interaction data and seals it in cryptographic logs.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:58.000
On top, the real-time flags layer monitors this data, detecting mismatches between customer intent and AI behaviour as they occur.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:06.000
These first two layers provide critical visibility, but are strictly observational, occurring after the AI executes an action.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:16.000
The third layer, the pre-action evidence gate, is active. It acts as a locally verified sandbox, enforcing a physical checkpoint to evaluate proposed actions.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:27.000
By combining data capture, real-time flagging, and pre-action evaluation, Obrioxia creates tamper-evident runtime evidence, a deployable enterprise utility.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Let's look at how this math works during a tangible commercial failure.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:38.000
A customer asks an enterprise AI travel agent to book a flight to Paris on Tuesday for under 250 pounds.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.000
But the AI model suffers a non-deterministic hallucination and drafts a completely incorrect itinerary.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
This flowchart maps the error.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Here is the original intent.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Paris, Tuesday, under 250 pounds.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:01.000
And here is the exact payload the AI actually attempts to execute, a flight to Madrid on Wednesday for 430 pounds.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Before the payment processor is pinged, the client's internal infrastructure intercepts the workflow and pauses the transaction.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:17.000
The client packages the original intent and hallucinated proposal together, routing them directly to the Obrioxia pre-action evidence gate.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:24.000
The gate evaluates the payload against predefined policy constraints, calculating the exact mathematical delta.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
The evaluation catches three violations.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:34.000
The 430-pound price limit is breached, Madrid does not match Paris, and Wednesday does not match Tuesday.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Obrioxia immediately generates a definitive block decision and attaches a flag requiring human approval.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Intercepting the hallucination stops immediate financial loss.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
It proves that catastrophic AI errors can be caught before execution.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
There is a crucial architectural boundary here.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Obrioxia provides the proof and evaluation, but it does not magically force-stop third-party AI systems from the outside.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Operating as an inline firewall or universal blocking proxy introduces unacceptable latency and stability risks for massive enterprise systems.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Instead, the standard for AI safety relies on a client-enforced decision.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:19.000
The Obrioxia checkpoint evaluates the data and sends a block payload back to the client's infrastructure.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Upon receiving the decision, the client's internal infrastructure physically severs the connection locally.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
This separation of powers is vital.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Enterprises maintain complete operational control over their infrastructure, while relying on a mathematically unbiased third-party entity to provide the pre-action policy checkpoint.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Now, step away from the IT integration and look at this from the perspective of a commercial underwriter reviewing a liability claim.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:57.000
An insurer cannot confidently write or accurately price a policy for agentic workflows if they cannot quantify the risk of non-deterministic failure.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:05.000
When an underwriter reviews a standard claim today, the absence of a verified evidence chain leaves them guessing.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.000
They cannot differentiate between what an AI was instructed to do and what it actually did.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:19.000
The introduction of a tamper-evident record provides the specific context needed to resolve these claims without ambiguity.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:29.000
Obrioxia takes the original intent, the proposed action, the final decision, and the explicit reasons and seals them all into a single cohesive file.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Providing cryptographic proof of the entire lifecycle removes the guesswork from claims reviews.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
It turns an uninsurable unknown into a highly structured, verifiable event.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:48.000
This process yields the ultimate output of the Obrioxia architecture, the underwriter-readable evidence pack.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:57.000
This pack organises complex interactions into structured policy condition evidence for immediate review by risk professionals and claims adjusters.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:06.000
It proves to auditors and regulators alike that a risky action was actively caught and flagged for human approval before execution could occur.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:13.000
Opaque logs and unverified guardrails no longer meet the evidentiary standards required for high-stakes enterprise deployments.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:25.000
AI governance policies can dictate what should happen, but only an immutable evidence chain provides the tamper-evident runtime evidence required to definitively prove what actually happened.
